# Build & Package — DLLs into pyRevit Extension

## CRITICAL: Two DLL Locations

Build outputs go to **TWO places** — both must be updated:

| Location | Path | Purpose |
|----------|------|---------|
| Repo (source) | `HD.extension/lib/net8/` | Git version control |
| pyRevit runtime | `%APPDATA%\pyRevit\extensions\HD.extension\lib\net8\` | **Revit loads DLLs from here** |

`Directory.Build.props` has a `SyncToPyRevit` target that auto-copies on build.
If build fails to sync (DLL locked), **close Revit first** then rebuild.

### Verify after build

```powershell
# Check both locations have same version
Get-Item "HD.extension\lib\net8\RevitChatLocal.dll" | Select LastWriteTime
Get-Item "$env:APPDATA\pyRevit\extensions\HD.extension\lib\net8\RevitChatLocal.dll" | Select LastWriteTime
```

If timestamps differ → DLLs are out of sync → Revit runs old code.

## Build Matrix (Hard Rule)

Always produce BOTH targets:

| Target Framework | Revit Versions |
|------------------|----------------|
| `net48` | 2023–2024 |
| `net8.0-windows` | 2025–2026 |

## Packaging (Copy Step)

Copy outputs to pyRevit extension lib folders:

```
<Ext>.extension/
  lib/
    net48/    # dll + all dependencies for Revit 2023–2024
    net8/     # dll + all dependencies for Revit 2025–2026
```

## Dependency Rule

If DLL has dependencies, place them alongside the DLL in the same lib folder.

## When user says "build to test in Revit"

1. Run `dotnet build ... --configuration Release`
2. Verify build log shows `→ pyRevit extensions` for each DLL
3. If any DLL shows copy error → remind user to close Revit first
4. After build, user must **restart Revit** (DLLs are locked while running)

## Never Do

- Do NOT ship separate `.addin` manifests for this workflow.
- Do NOT point pyRevit to `bin/Debug` or `bin/Release` paths in production builds.
- Do NOT assume dependencies are shared — each lib folder must be self-contained.
- Do NOT forget to sync to pyRevit runtime folder — repo copy alone is NOT enough.
